  "prompt": "My partner has a hard lump near his spine in the upper back, that moves when pressed on. There is significant pain in the area surrounding it. We are looking at various options, such as lipomas, spine spurs, lymphs, spinal tumour? What could it be?",
  "response": "It's important to note that I cannot provide a definitive diagnosis, and the best course of action is to consult a healthcare professional for a proper medical evaluation. However, I can discuss some potential possibilities:\n\nPossible Causes:\n1. Lipoma\n- Benign fatty tumor\n- Usually soft and movable\n- Typically painless (which differs from your description)\n\n2. Muscle Knot/Trigger Point\n- Can be painful\n- Often related to muscle tension or injury\n- Moves when pressed\n\n3. Cyst\n- Can be painful\n- Movable\n- Varies in size\n\n4. Bone Spur (Osteophyte)\n- Bony projection along joint edges\n- Can cause pain\n- Usually less movable\n\n5. Lymph Node Enlargement\n- Can be painful if infected\n- Typically movable\n- Could indicate infection or inflammation\n\n6. More Serious Possibilities\n- Bone tumor\n- Spinal tumor\n- Herniated disc\n- Nerve-related issue\n\nRecommended Actions:\n- See a healthcare professional\n- Get imaging (X-ray, MRI)\n- Have a physical examination\n- Discuss pain and movement characteristics\n\nA medical professional can provide an accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment.",
